&gt;&gt;Glen: Well, I just threw this in because
I think it's interesting in that this is a

00:03:38.349 --> 00:03:43.810
very early map of the coast of California.
Originally, there was a misconception that

00:03:43.810 --> 00:03:49.230
lasted through, all throughout the 18th Century
that California was an island. And this is,

00:03:49.230 --> 00:03:59.069
they corrected that eventually and this is
a map of the coast of California, where they

00:03:59.069 --> 00:04:04.689
actually call it the City of the Angels, cause
that was the original name of the city and

00:04:04.689 --> 00:04:10.830
the city was the City of Los Angeles de--,
I can't even pronounce Porciúncula, but it's

00:04:10.830 --> 00:04:17.440
the river; Los Angeles River. One of the first
maps I wanted to use in the book, and this

00:04:17.440 --> 00:04:24.970
does look pretty compressed, this is the Kirkman
Harriman Map. It was created by a very eccentric

00:04:24.970 --> 00:04:32.220
columnist at the Los Angeles Times. Kirkman
Harriman, as it turns out, was a man who was

00:04:32.220 --> 00:04:37.490
one of the first people to care for the indigent
in Los Angeles and he ran the county farm

00:04:37.490 --> 00:04:43.660
where they would literally take care of homeless
people and so forth. I believe that he did

00:04:43.660 --> 00:04:52.860
a lot of the research on this because he tracked
a lot of these kinds of things. Anyway, they

00:04:52.860 --> 00:04:58.700
created this map and it's amazing in that
it was done in 1938, but it portrays the area

00:04:58.700 --> 00:05:06.669
in 1860. And the thing about it is there's
layers of historical fact in this map. It

00:05:06.669 --> 00:05:14.440
shows the early trails, the roads that people
traveled on, it shows battle sites and it

00:05:14.440 --> 00:05:20.069
shows where the Indian villages were. And
I think there's a small misconception that

00:05:20.069 --> 00:05:25.050
there wasn't much of a Native American presence
here and there was much more than you would

00:05:25.050 --> 00:05:31.550
expect. That's what Santa Monica looks like
on this map and you can see there were villages

00:05:31.550 --> 00:05:37.300
here. It was the Tongva Indians and further
north it was the Chumash Indians. Eventually,

00:05:37.300 --> 00:05:45.720
they named them; they called them Gabrielinos,
or the Fernandinos, which is really an Anglo

00:05:45.720 --> 00:05:52.050
naming of the Tongva Indians. They formed
the original settlement here, which was Yang-na,

00:05:52.050 --> 00:05:57.449
which was here thousands of years; they thrived.
This was one of the most successful tribes

00:05:57.449 --> 00:06:05.349
in North America, actually. But they lived
in a Stone Age. They didn't really need to

00:06:05.349 --> 00:06:09.950
do much more than what they were doing, which
was enjoy this beautiful weather and this

00:06:09.950 --> 00:06:11.870
harsh winter day here in Santa Monica.

00:06:11.870 --> 00:06:13.639
[laughter]

00:06:13.639 --> 00:06:22.280
And they dug things out of the sand, they
fished, they hunted and they very rarely fought.

00:06:22.280 --> 00:06:30.621
This was a very, until the Spaniards came
there was very little conflict for them. Also,

00:06:30.621 --> 00:06:36.639
on this map you'll see these battle sites.
Those little crossed swords at the top of

00:06:36.639 --> 00:06:41.030
this, right here, you can see that's still
Los Angeles River at the top flowing through

00:06:41.030 --> 00:06:48.200
there. That is like the Cahuenga Pass right
there. And that's the Battle of La Providencia.

00:06:48.200 --> 00:06:55.919
That was a battle in which California fought
the Americans and because in this area, most

00:06:55.919 --> 00:07:00.710
of the battle were fought between family and
friends. They didn't really kill people, they

00:07:00.710 --> 00:07:05.090
just kind of, too bad people don't do that
now, if they had drive-by shootings where

00:07:05.090 --> 00:07:11.919
they'd shoot into the air. So, in this battle,
they actually only killed a mule and injured

00:07:11.919 --> 00:07:20.180
a horse and that was the casualties for the
Battle of La Providencia. You can see at the

00:07:20.180 --> 00:07:25.879
heart of this map, the thing that amazes me
about it is if you took this and reproduced

00:07:25.879 --> 00:07:32.080
it on a transparency, you could put this right
over a map of the freeways today and you'd

00:07:32.080 --> 00:07:40.870
be amazed to see how many of these trails
end up being freeways, or major thoroughfares.

00:07:40.870 --> 00:07:45.830
So, it's actually, on this map, you'll see,
Yes.

00:07:45.830 --> 00:07:48.970
&gt;&gt;audience #2: When was this map created?

00:07:48.970 --> 00:07:52.470
&gt;&gt;Glen: It was created in 1938, but it portrays
1860.

00:07:52.470 --> 00:08:01.370
&gt;&gt;audience #2: Just to repeat, this is as,
intended to look as it did in 1860--

00:08:01.370 --> 00:08:03.330
&gt;&gt;Glen: 1860, but it's layered with historical--

00:08:03.330 --> 00:08:06.930
&gt;&gt;audience #2: Right, well are we seeing 1770,
January 16th here, so--

00:08:06.930 --> 00:08:13.570
&gt;&gt;Glen: Right, those would be the events that
happened and a lot of the, when the Spanish

00:08:13.570 --> 00:08:20.539
explorers came through here, first they just
sailed by in the 1540s and it looked nice,

00:08:20.539 --> 00:08:28.250
but they just kept going. Then eventually,
they had these inland expeditions and they

00:08:28.250 --> 00:08:37.060
were commissioned by Spanish government to
seek out and create missions that would be

00:08:37.060 --> 00:08:48.680
a backbone of civilization. So, on this map
you're gonna see up there, oh, you can see

00:08:48.680 --> 00:08:58.140
Eagle Rock. There's Hollywood over there and
the roads going south, that would be like

00:08:58.140 --> 00:09:06.519
the 110 freeway and you can actually see the
San Bernardino freeway there, the Hollywood

00:09:06.519 --> 00:09:14.839
freeway. All these, even though these maps
existed in the past and the present and also

00:09:14.839 --> 00:09:23.320
they're going to continue, the Mexican colonial,
Spanish colonial American period, they also

00:09:23.320 --> 00:09:34.820
meld together in this one historical flow.
Which is why I threw this in because I thought

00:09:34.820 --> 00:09:41.010
this was quite interesting. This is de Anza's,
the de Anza's trail as he came through here

00:09:41.010 --> 00:09:46.779
and studying it historically, we can see that
he took the 101 to the 134 and then he got

00:09:46.779 --> 00:09:47.779
on the 60, headed out toward--

00:09:47.779 --> 00:09:48.779
[laughter]

00:09:48.779 --> 00:09:49.779
&gt;&gt;audience #3: That's what he wrote and he
said--

00:09:49.779 --> 00:09:55.910
&gt;&gt;audience #4: And there was a Sigalert up
there, heading towards the County Fair.

00:09:55.910 --> 00:10:06.120
&gt;&gt;Glen: The other, the next period really,
after of course the native Americans is the

00:10:06.120 --> 00:10:13.190
Spanish and Mexican colonial periods where
they divided the city, or the area, into these

00:10:13.190 --> 00:10:20.540
ranchos. And at first, it was a very, it was
1783. It was the first rancho and it was a

00:10:20.540 --> 00:10:27.950
very informal process in which the people
that had settled here originally they actually

00:10:27.950 --> 00:10:36.529
brought 44 people up here. Eleven families
came up here from Mexico on foot; walked up

00:10:36.529 --> 00:10:45.660
and in 1781, founded the Pueblo of Los Angeles.
And then, as time went on, they needed a place

00:10:45.660 --> 00:10:52.070
to graze their cattle and so forth, so they
would just ask the governor, "May I have land?"

00:10:52.070 --> 00:10:57.771
And they would be granted these ranchos. And
in some cases, I think one of the ranchos,

00:10:57.771 --> 00:11:05.279
Tijuana, he asked the governor and he said,
"Sure, you can have the land to the water."

00:11:05.279 --> 00:11:10.980
And that went from Compton to the Pacific
Ocean. Some of these ranchos were absolutely

00:11:10.980 --> 00:11:24.760
immense. That's the Treaty of Guadalupe of
Hidalgo, which we'll get to later. The other

00:11:24.760 --> 00:11:34.180
thing about these, actually the ranch showed
here is ironically entitled Rancho Santa Monica,

00:11:34.180 --> 00:11:41.590
or one of them. There's Boca de Santa Monica,
also. At the center of all these ranchos is

00:11:41.590 --> 00:11:47.440
the four square leads and that was granted
by the Spanish government. Where it says "Pueblo

00:11:47.440 --> 00:11:57.600
de Los Angeles" that was an area that was
basically given to the government of the city.

00:11:57.600 --> 00:12:07.639
And it's quite important that they controlled
that little area and we'll see why this city

00:12:07.639 --> 00:12:13.990
grew because there are reasons why they were
able to annex all this territory all around

00:12:13.990 --> 00:12:23.089
the city and it has to do with having this
right from the Spanish crown. I did a program

00:12:23.089 --> 00:12:34.040
with DJ Waldie, who's a historian. He was
called a rock star historian. Anyway, he explained

00:12:34.040 --> 00:12:36.940
why Los Angeles is crooked--

00:12:36.940 --> 00:12:38.910
&gt;&gt;audience #5: [inaudible]

00:12:38.910 --> 00:12:40.220
&gt;&gt;Glen: Yeah.

00:12:40.220 --> 00:12:41.530
[Glen laughs]

00:12:41.530 --> 00:12:47.740
Geographically crooked. It goes back to a
Roman ideals of the way you should lay out

00:12:47.740 --> 00:12:53.839
a city and it was supposedly that you would
cock the streets at a 45 degree angle, but

00:12:53.839 --> 00:12:59.389
in Los Angeles, because of the geography and
the way the city was set up, it's actually

00:12:59.389 --> 00:13:07.029
38%. So the city is kind of, and you'll see
that in later maps and the maps that are used

00:13:07.029 --> 00:13:12.389
in the book, you'll see later when they started
trying to create a grid like cities on the

00:13:12.389 --> 00:13:20.300
East Coast, you'll see that the Pueblos tilted
to the side. But then again, it was all based

00:13:20.300 --> 00:13:25.070
on this premise that the winds blew from the
North, South, East and West, which they don't

00:13:25.070 --> 00:13:29.740
always do that. Not even in Santa Monica,
so.

00:13:29.740 --> 00:13:33.190
[Glen clears throat]

