You know, I think those are supposed to be
the missions. Although, there is an extra

00:13:52.040 --> 00:14:00.380
one there. Oh, you know what that is? That's
the plaza. That's the plaza church, cause

00:14:00.380 --> 00:14:12.380
that was the center. That was the center of
the pueblo. Now, even though this is a pictorial

00:14:12.380 --> 00:14:17.850
map and people think of it as plebeian, I
just wanted to use it in the book because

00:14:17.850 --> 00:14:23.740
it shows how the city was laid out; how the
whole area was laid out. And because this

00:14:23.740 --> 00:14:28.620
is a typical deseño, these were the maps
that were done of the rancho. And you can

00:14:28.620 --> 00:14:36.690
see this looks like something that maybe your
kid did in 3rd grade, but surveying was so

00:14:36.690 --> 00:14:42.180
primitive in those days, the way they measured
these ranchos is they would take two horsemen

00:14:42.180 --> 00:14:48.839
on racing horses with a big rope in-between
them and they would ride like this; back and

00:14:48.839 --> 00:14:55.980
forth, back and forth. And that's how they
would measure. But once statehood came, the

00:14:55.980 --> 00:15:01.680
people that were gonna buy these ranchos;
they didn't want to rely on that kind of loose.

00:15:01.680 --> 00:15:08.880
So anyway, we'll get to that about how they
actually did survey these later on. This represents

00:15:08.880 --> 00:15:16.380
two different things. This is what's called
the land case map and first it represents

00:15:16.380 --> 00:15:22.800
the missions, which were these outposts of
civilization. And of all the missions along

00:15:22.800 --> 00:15:27.690
California, Mission San Gabriel is probably
the most successful mission; the one that

00:15:27.690 --> 00:15:35.620
really worked the best. But in 1833, they
secularized all the missions and they basically,

00:15:35.620 --> 00:15:44.329
eventually sold those lands and they became
part of other ranchos. Now, when the Mexican

00:15:44.329 --> 00:15:50.800
government took over, and this is a very loose
control of the Californians who lived here,

00:15:50.800 --> 00:15:56.380
the Californians who lived in Los Angeles
area paid very little attention to government.

00:15:56.380 --> 00:15:57.380
So--

00:15:57.380 --> 00:15:58.380
&gt;&gt;audience #6: [inaudible]

00:15:58.380 --> 00:16:09.759
&gt;&gt;Glen: No. [laughing] So, once that Treaty
of Guadalupe Hidalgo was settled, the US and

00:16:09.759 --> 00:16:15.670
Mexico they said, "We will recognize these
rancho lands." So, they heaved a sigh of relief

00:16:15.670 --> 00:16:22.899
while these rancho owners. Unfortunately,
when statehood came, Uncle Sam wanted taxes

00:16:22.899 --> 00:16:30.860
paid and this was not a cash economy here.
Most of these people were cattle ranchers

00:16:30.860 --> 00:16:36.580
and would literally drive Longhorn cattle
from here all the way up to San Francisco.

00:16:36.580 --> 00:16:45.350
So, they basically had to sell their land
and the US government said that you have to

00:16:45.350 --> 00:16:50.860
prove your title to the lands. And that meant
that they had to hire lawyers, they had to

00:16:50.860 --> 00:16:57.540
survey the property, they had to send people
all the way up to Washington, DC for these

00:16:57.540 --> 00:17:06.100
hearings. And these would take 15, 18 years.
In the meantime, they were completely drained

00:17:06.100 --> 00:17:15.690
and most of the, or many, of these rancho
owners who lived this very beautiful, idyllic

00:17:15.690 --> 00:17:22.460
life that you picture old California, like
the old Zorro episodes, they ended up in Sonora

00:17:22.460 --> 00:17:28.700
Town, which is where Alvera Street is now;
absolutely impoverished with not a penny to

00:17:28.700 --> 00:17:35.710
their names. This particular map here represents
the case of William Workman, who was at one

00:17:35.710 --> 00:17:42.050
time mayor of Los Angeles, and one of the
very first bankers. And he was ruined by this

00:17:42.050 --> 00:17:53.530
and he eventually actually committed suicide.
This is what the city looked like. This was

00:17:53.530 --> 00:18:00.860
a sketch done by a German artist. He's an
engineer and an artist. As they came down,

00:18:00.860 --> 00:18:04.790
they were trying to find a rail route for
the Mississippi to the Pacific Ocean. There

00:18:04.790 --> 00:18:10.110
was no railroads in Los Angeles until the
1870s. So, they were trying to determine a

00:18:10.110 --> 00:18:20.670
route to take and this is a sketch that this
German artist, Coppel, made. And you can see,

00:18:20.670 --> 00:18:24.860
I guess I can't use a pointer, right? Or,
is there a pointer?

