00:44:55.900 --> 00:45:01.580
1903, and it's called the Automobile and Miners
Road Map, which is kind of mysterious because

00:45:01.580 --> 00:45:05.650
I'm not sure what the miners had to do with
this. And originally, when I saw the map,

00:45:05.650 --> 00:45:13.770
I thought these little dots were oil wells
because this is when they had discovered oil.

00:45:13.770 --> 00:45:20.660
Doheny is the guy that discovered oil over
by La Brea Tar Pits. It's amazing that they

00:45:20.660 --> 00:45:26.930
sharpened a eucalyptus tree and then drove
it into the ground. That's how they first

00:45:26.930 --> 00:45:33.620
did oil discoveries. Anyway, this is when
the speed limit was eight miles per hour,

00:45:33.620 --> 00:45:39.020
but you can see that there it's still really
sprawled out. So, Los Angeles has always been

00:45:39.020 --> 00:45:49.060
this kind of sprawling, and it has a lot to
do with the ranchos, it has a lot to do with

00:45:49.060 --> 00:45:57.150
streetcars. This is what downtown looked like
in 1913 and this is kind of a watershed year

00:45:57.150 --> 00:46:05.670
because the city of Los Angeles was the very
first city to have a population boom after

00:46:05.670 --> 00:46:13.710
mass production of automobiles. And so, the
city, even though World War I was on the horizon,

00:46:13.710 --> 00:46:22.610
was really booming and there was a lot of
building and there were, in downtown, you

00:46:22.610 --> 00:46:28.940
can see that this is an amazing map, too,
cause it's an orthographic projection. And

00:46:28.940 --> 00:46:35.880
it's like an aerial photo. You can see the
top there. Again, there's a central park.

00:46:35.880 --> 00:46:42.260
Five years later, that became Pershing Square.
I guess Pershing was a hero in World War I.

00:46:42.260 --> 00:46:50.300
And there were showing movies; the first movies
were being shown in downtown and the next

00:46:50.300 --> 00:46:57.270
year, the Panama Canal opened and the Harbor
had already been approved, so then Los Angeles

00:46:57.270 --> 00:47:07.510
just really took off as an industrial power.
There again is Central Park and there's also

00:47:07.510 --> 00:47:12.490
Hamburger's Department Store is in there.
That's where they had the movable staircase,

00:47:12.490 --> 00:47:19.320
they called it. This was done much later,
but this is an example of one of these tourist

00:47:19.320 --> 00:47:28.490
come-on maps. I love this one because it has
some personal significance for me and I just

00:47:28.490 --> 00:47:37.360
think it's so funny because this man was a
German, and for some reason, he did the regular

00:47:37.360 --> 00:47:44.890
tourist thing. So, on this you see the Brown
Derby and the Groman's Chinese and the Hollywood

00:47:44.890 --> 00:47:50.690
Bowl and things like that, but when he gets
to Santa Monica, what does he have? The Crystal

00:47:50.690 --> 00:47:53.369
Pier nude sunbaths.

00:47:53.369 --> 00:47:55.369
[laughter]

00:47:55.369 --> 00:48:03.750
And he also has, see there's Clover Field
up there. There's the Venice oil fields, Sunset

00:48:03.750 --> 00:48:12.730
Pier and he has the, my father happened to
be a craps dealer on a gambling boat. They

00:48:12.730 --> 00:48:18.820
used to take these ships and put them off
the coast outside of jurisdiction of the law

00:48:18.820 --> 00:48:22.990
and they would gamble out there, so my father
was a craps dealer there. So, that's not the

00:48:22.990 --> 00:48:29.240
one he was one, but in this, this guy who
did the map included them. This one here,

00:48:29.240 --> 00:48:36.820
I think, is the quintessence of the Southern
California good life. You have all the flora

00:48:36.820 --> 00:48:44.550
and the fauna and everything just looks, everything
is like, washed in the sun and again, there's

00:48:44.550 --> 00:48:53.300
Santa Monica. I tailored this for the Google
audience. Everybody's horseback riding and

00:48:53.300 --> 00:48:56.250
