00:48:57.250 --> 00:49:06.840
And there's a whale on the, see there's, but
he does include their oil well. See the oil

00:49:06.840 --> 00:49:18.240
wells there, gushing oil along with some of
the actual, I think that's 1932. So, the called

00:49:18.240 --> 00:49:27.869
the Coliseum the Olympic Stadium, cause this
was the year of the Olympics in '32. This

00:49:27.869 --> 00:49:36.670
is, to me, the greatest map ever. This is
a Joe Morrow. He was an immigrant from Uruguay;

00:49:36.670 --> 00:49:43.040
amazing artist. He was a great sculptor, he
was a painter. When he was 14 years old, he

00:49:43.040 --> 00:49:49.150
already had a job as a cartoonist at the Boston
Herald and he did these things they called

00:49:49.150 --> 00:49:56.950
"carts." And at first, I think he did them
for his children for fun and this one he did

00:49:56.950 --> 00:50:05.990
in Los Angeles in 1942, and it's just incredible.
It's just like a history of the city. And

00:50:05.990 --> 00:50:13.770
everything around the edges there, at the
top, that's Los Angeles history and this man

00:50:13.770 --> 00:50:18.750
lived with the Indians and he was an expert
on Californios; the pre-statehood California

00:50:18.750 --> 00:50:25.720
history. He wrote a book on the Californios
and everything in those illustrations is exactly

00:50:25.720 --> 00:50:29.970
correct, right down to the hair styles and
the clothes they're wearing. Although, at

00:50:29.970 --> 00:50:34.940
the bottom I really like, there's these, it
shows the population growth of the city and

00:50:34.940 --> 00:50:40.500
its women wearing bathing suits, blowing up
these balloons that say, "80 thousand people"

00:50:40.500 --> 00:50:45.550
or whatever. But it has like, when electricity
was invented, when the Pacific Coast League

00:50:45.550 --> 00:50:55.470
baseball started, earthquakes, the Pony Express,
which came through here. This is a close-up

00:50:55.470 --> 00:51:01.840
